Title: Still no loading indicator while results are being fetched

Finding:
The prior medium finding was not addressed. In render() (src/app/render-orchestrator.ts), the results container is cleared synchronously (`resultsEl.innerHTML = '';`) and then the route data is awaited with no loading, skeleton, or 'Loading…' state in between. The status footer is intentionally left untouched to preserve navigation targets, so during the fetch the user sees an empty table and an empty/stale status with no indication that work is in progress. This hurts perceived performance and can look like a broken or empty UI, especially on slower connections or larger directories. The lifecycle is newly authored in render-orchestrator.ts and remains unchanged.

Fix instructions (follow exactly; make targeted, minimal changes):
In src/app/render-orchestrator.ts render(), after clearing the results container (`resultsEl.innerHTML = '';`) and BEFORE the `await getApi().browse(...)` / `.search(...)` calls, render a lightweight loading placeholder into the results container so the user sees that work is in progress. For example, set `resultsEl.textContent = 'Loading…';` (or append a skeleton element with an appropriate class). Ensure the loading state is replaced when data arrives (renderBrowse/renderSearch already replace resultsEl contents) and also replaced in the catch block (which sets resultsEl.textContent to the error message). The render-race guard (`if (myToken !== renderToken) return;`) must still short-circuit superseded renders. Keep it minimal — a text node or simple element — and add a CSS class if you want a styled skeleton. Verify the loading state appears during a slow fetch and is cleared on success/error.

